Credit Card Fraud Detection

Abstract

We detect anomalous behavior in credit card transactions using the dataset. In the dataset, there are 492 anomalies out of 284,807 transactions, and each transaction is described by 30 features and 1 label. Among the 30 features, there are 28 features transformed by PCA and 2 (non-transformed) features called Time and Amount. The label called Class is denoted by 1 if the transaction is a fraud, and 0 otherwise. Since the dataset is highly imbalanced, the \(F_{1}\) score is used.

The problem can be solved by supervised learning and anomaly detection. For the supervised learning, the dataset will be divided into 3 parts: 60% normal and oversampling anomalous transactions for training (or undersampling normal and 60% anomalous transactions for training), 20% normal and 20% anomalous transactions for cross-validation, and the rest 20% normal and 20% anomalous transactions for testing. For the anomaly detection, 60% normal transactions for training, 20% normal and 50% anomalous transactions for cross-validation, and the rest 20% normal and 50% anomalous transactions for testing. In particular, we will use logistic regression with regularization and Gaussian models. The results on the test sets are summarized as follows. Note that all parameters are optimized by the cross-validation sets.

resSupervised = data.frame("Supervised Model"=c("Logistic Regression with Oversampling","Logistic Regression with Undersampling"),
                     "Regularized Parameter"=c(0,2010),
                     Threshold=c(0.9,0.5),
                     Precision=c(0.42,0.92),
                     Recall=c(0.848,0.808),
                     F1=c(0.562,0.86))
print(resSupervised)
resAnomaly = data.frame("Anomaly Detection"=c("Gaussian","Multivariate Gaussian","Multivariate Gaussian"),
                     Features=c("All","All","Some"),
                     Threshold=c(1.609*10^(-114),1.323*10^(-142),1.007*10^(-52)),
                     Precision=c(0.311,0.568,0.917),
                     Recall=c(0.366,0.732,0.764),
                     F1=c(0.336,0.639,0.834))
print(resAnomaly)

The performance of the multivariate Gaussian model with selected features (the last row in the 2nd table) is close to the one using logistic regression with regularization trained on undersampling normal dataset (the last row in the 1st table). However, the former model requires selecting features carefully. By using logistic regression with regularization, we are able to refine a subset of features based on the \(F_{1}\) score; and then we apply multivariate Gaussian model on the refined dataset.

Note that we implement logistic regression with regularization, Gaussian and Multivariate Gaussian models in R, and algorithms to select the regularized parameter and threshold using \(F_{1}\) score on a cross-validation set.

The data

fraud = read.csv("~/Downloads/Data/CreditCardFraudDetection/creditcard.csv")
fraud = cbind(scale(fraud[,-ncol(fraud)]), Class=fraud[,ncol(fraud)])
fraud0 = fraud[fraud[,ncol(fraud)]==0,]
fraud1 = fraud[fraud[,ncol(fraud)]==1,]
set.seed(123)
idx0 = sample(1:nrow(fraud0))
idx1 = sample(1:nrow(fraud1))
fraud0 = fraud0[idx0,]
fraud1 = fraud1[idx1,]

Splitting data

ratioTrain = 0.6

Undersampling and oversampling

set.seed(123)
# Undersampling
idx_under = sample(1:nrow(XY_train0), size = nrow(fraud1), replace = F)
XY_train0_under = XY_train0[idx_under,]
XY_train_under = rbind(XY_train0_under, XY_train1)
XY_train_under = XY_train_under[sample(1:nrow(XY_train_under)),]
X_train_under = XY_train_under[,-ncol(XY_train_under)]
y_train_under = XY_train_under[,ncol(XY_train_under)]
# Oversampling
idx_over = sample(1:nrow(XY_train1), size = nrow(XY_train0), replace = T)
XY_train1_over = XY_train1[idx_over,]
XY_train_over = rbind(XY_train0, XY_train1_over)
XY_train_over = XY_train_over[sample(1:nrow(XY_train_over)),]
X_train_over = XY_train_over[,-ncol(XY_train_over)]
y_train_over = XY_train_over[,ncol(XY_train_over)]
XY_val = rbind(XY_val0, XY_val1)
XY_val = XY_val[sample(1:nrow(XY_val)),]
X_val = XY_val[,-ncol(XY_val)]
y_val = XY_val[,ncol(XY_val)]
XY_test = rbind(XY_test0, XY_test1)
XY_test = XY_test[sample(1:nrow(XY_test)),]
X_test = XY_test[,-ncol(XY_test)]
y_test = XY_test[,ncol(XY_test)]

Gaussian model

Splitting data

set.seed(123)
# 60% non-fraud for training, 20% non-fraud and 50% fraud for validation, the rest 20% non-fraud and 50% fraud for test
ratioTrain = 0.6
ratioVal = 0.2
ratioTest = 0.2
XY_train = splitData(fraud0, ratioTrain, ratioVal, ratioTest)[[1]]
XY_val0 = splitData(fraud0, ratioTrain, ratioVal, ratioTest)[[2]]
XY_test0 = splitData(fraud0, ratioTrain, ratioVal, ratioTest)[[3]]
XY_val1 = fraud1[1:floor(0.5*nrow(fraud1)),]
XY_test1 = fraud1[(floor(0.5*nrow(fraud1))+1):nrow(fraud1),]
X_train = XY_train[,-ncol(XY_train)]
y_train = XY_train[,ncol(XY_train)]
XY_val = rbind(XY_val0, XY_val1)
XY_val = XY_val[sample(1:nrow(XY_val)),]
X_val = XY_val[,-ncol(XY_val)]
y_val = XY_val[,ncol(XY_val)]
XY_test = rbind(XY_test0, XY_test1)
XY_test = XY_test[sample(1:nrow(XY_test)),]
X_test = XY_test[,-ncol(XY_test)]
y_test = XY_test[,ncol(XY_test)]

Gaussian model with all features

mu = estimateGaussian(X_train)[[1]]
sigma2 = estimateGaussian(X_train)[[2]]
p_val = multivariateGaussian(X_val, mu, sigma2)
stepsize = 10^2
L1 = selectThresholdGaussian(y_val, p_val, stepsize)

Multivariate Gaussian with a subset of features

X_train_reduced = X_train[,featureRank_under]
X_val_reduced = X_val[,featureRank_under]
X_test_reduced = X_test[,featureRank_under]
Eps = rep(0, ncol(X_train_reduced))
F1s = rep(0, ncol(X_train_reduced))
for (j in 2:ncol(X_train_reduced)) {
  mu = estimateMultiGaussian(X_train_reduced[,1:j])[[1]]
  Sigma = estimateMultiGaussian(X_train_reduced[,1:j])[[2]]
  p_val = multivariateGaussian(X_val_reduced[,1:j], mu, Sigma)
  stepsize = 10^2
  L = selectThresholdGaussian(y_val, p_val, stepsize)
  epsilon = L[[1]]
  L1 = selectThresholdGaussianFurther(y_val, p_val, epsilon)
  Eps[j] = L1[[1]]
  F1s[j] = L1[[2]]
}
library(ggplot2)
ggplot(data.frame(Eps=1:ncol(X_train_reduced), F1=F1s), aes(Eps, F1)) + geom_point() + geom_line() +
  xlab("Features") +
  ggtitle(paste("Selecting Best Features", which.max(F1s), "Threshold =", Eps[which.max(F1s)], "F1 =", round(F1s[which.max(F1s)],3)))
